# Angular Signal Forms

Signal Forms are the **recommended and only** approach for handling forms in modern Angular applications (v21+). They provide a reactive, type-safe, and model-driven way to manage form state using Angular Signals.

## Critical Rules

- **ALWAYS** use the Signal Forms API from `@angular/forms/signals` for all form-related functionality.
- **NEVER** use `FormControl`, `FormGroup`, `FormArray`, or `FormBuilder` from `@angular/forms`. Signal Forms replace these entirely.
- **NEVER** use `null` or `undefined` as initial values in the model. Use `''` for strings, `0` for numbers, `[]` for arrays, `false` for booleans.
- **NEVER** use HTML attributes `min`, `max`, `value`, `[value]`, `[disabled]`, `[readonly]` on elements using `[formField]`. Use schema rules instead.
- Signal Forms does **NOT** have a builder pattern.

## Imports

Everything comes from `@angular/forms/signals`:

```ts
import {
  // Core
  form, FormField, submit,
  // Validators
  required, email, min, max, minLength, maxLength, pattern,
  // Field state rules
  disabled, hidden, readonly, debounce,
  // Schema helpers
  schema, applyWhen, applyEach,
  // Custom validation
  validate, validateAsync, validateHttp, validateStandardSchema,
  // Metadata
  metadata,
} from '@angular/forms/signals';
```

## Creating a Form

Use the `form()` function with a WritableSignal model. The form structure mirrors your data shape automatically.

```ts
import { Component, signal } from '@angular/core';
import { form, FormField, required, email } from '@angular/forms/signals';

@Component({
  imports: [FormField],
  // ...
})
export class MyComponent {
  model = signal({
    name: '',       // NEVER null
    email: '',      // NEVER null
    age: 0,         // NEVER null
    items: [] as string[],  // NEVER null
  });

  myForm = form(this.model, (s) => {
    required(s.name);
    required(s.email);
    email(s.email);
  });
}
```

## Template Binding

Import `FormField` and use the `[formField]` directive:

```html
<input [formField]="myForm.name" />
<input type="email" [formField]="myForm.email" />
<input type="number" [formField]="myForm.age" />
<input type="checkbox" [formField]="myForm.isActive" />
<select [formField]="myForm.country">
  <option value="us">US</option>
</select>
<select multiple [formField]="myForm.tags">
  <option value="a">A</option>
</select>
```

## FormField vs FieldState (Critical Concept)

A `FormField` is the structural tree you navigate. You **MUST CALL** it as a function to get the `FieldState` with reactive signals.

```ts
// FormField (structural) — navigate to fields
myForm.name;              // FormField — NO state signals here

// FieldState (reactive) — CALL the field
myForm.name();            // FieldState — has .value(), .valid(), etc.
myForm.name().touched();  // Signal<boolean>
myForm.name().value();    // Signal<string>

// WRONG:
myForm.name.touched();    // ERROR: touched() doesn't exist on FormField
myForm().name.touched();  // ERROR: myForm() is FieldState, not navigable
```

In templates:
```html
<!-- CORRECT -->
@if (myForm.email().touched() && myForm.email().invalid()) {
  <span>{{ myForm.email().errors()[0].message }}</span>
}

<!-- WRONG -->
@if (myForm.email.touched()) { ... }
```

## Accessing State

```ts
// Form-level (call the form root)
myForm().valid();     // Signal<boolean>
myForm().invalid();   // Signal<boolean>
myForm().dirty();     // Signal<boolean>
myForm().touched();   // Signal<boolean>
myForm().pending();   // Signal<boolean>
myForm().errors();    // Signal<ValidationError[]>
myForm().value();     // Full model value
myForm().reset();     // Reset the form

// Field-level (call the field)
myForm.name().valid();
myForm.name().dirty();
myForm.name().touched();
myForm.name().errors();
myForm.name().value();

// Array length — structural, NO parentheses
myForm.items.length;  // NOT myForm.items().length
```

## Validation

Define rules in the schema function passed to `form()`:

```ts
myForm = form(this.model, (s) => {
  required(s.name, { message: 'Name is required' });
  email(s.email, { message: 'Invalid email' });
  min(s.age, 18);
  max(s.age, 100);
  minLength(s.password, 8);
  maxLength(s.bio, 500);
  pattern(s.zipCode, /^\d{5}$/);
});
```

### Conditional Required (only `required` supports `when`)

```ts
required(s.driversLicense, {
  when({ valueOf }) {
    return valueOf(s.age) >= 16;
  },
});
```

### Custom Validation

```ts
validate(s.username, ({ value }) => {
  if (value() === 'admin') {
    return { kind: 'reserved', message: 'Username is reserved' };
  }
  return undefined; // No error — return undefined, NOT null
});
```

### Cross-Field Validation

```ts
validate(s.confirmPassword, ({ value, valueOf }) => {
  if (value() !== valueOf(s.password)) {
    return { kind: 'mismatch', message: 'Passwords do not match' };
  }
  return undefined;
});
```

### Validator Context

The callback receives a context object:

```ts
validate(s.field, ({
  value,      // Signal<T>: current field value
  valueOf,    // (path) => T: read OTHER fields' values
  state,      // FieldState<T>: this field's state
  stateOf,    // (path) => FieldState: other fields' state
  pathKeys,   // Signal<string[]>: path from root
}) => { ... });
```

## Async Validation

Use `validateAsync()` — all four options are **REQUIRED**:

```ts
validateAsync(s.username, {
  params: ({ value }) => value(),          // MUST be a function
  factory: (username) => resource({
    params: username,                      // Use 'params', NOT 'request'
    loader: async ({ params: val }) => { /* ... */ },
  }),
  onSuccess: (result) => result.taken
    ? { kind: 'taken', message: 'Already taken' }
    : undefined,
  onError: () => ({ kind: 'error', message: 'Check failed' }),  // REQUIRED
});
```

## HTTP Validation

```ts
validateHttp(s.username, {
  request: ({ value }) => `/api/check?username=${value()}`,
  onSuccess: (response) => response.taken
    ? { kind: 'taken', message: 'Already taken' }
    : null,
  onError: () => ({ kind: 'error', message: 'Network error' }),
});
```

## Field State Rules

```ts
disabled(s.field, ({ valueOf }) => valueOf(s.role) !== 'admin');
hidden(s.shippingAddress, ({ valueOf }) => valueOf(s.sameAsBilling));
readonly(s.createdAt);
debounce(s.searchQuery, 300);
```

## Submitting

The callback **MUST** be `async`:

```ts
import { submit } from '@angular/forms/signals';

onSubmit() {
  submit(this.myForm, async () => {
    await this.apiService.save(this.model());
  });
}
```

Disable the submit button:
```html
<button [disabled]="myForm().invalid() || myForm().pending()">Submit</button>
```

## Arrays with applyEach

Callback takes **ONE** argument only (no index):

```ts
applyEach(s.items, (item) => {
  required(item.name);
  min(item.quantity, 1);
});
```

Template iteration:
```html
@for (item of myForm.items; track $index) {
  <input [formField]="item.name" />
  <button (click)="removeItem($index)">Remove</button>
}
```

Add/remove items by updating the model signal:
```ts
addItem() {
  this.model.update(m => ({ ...m, items: [...m.items, { name: '', quantity: 1 }] }));
}
removeItem(index: number) {
  this.model.update(m => ({ ...m, items: m.items.filter((_, i) => i !== index) }));
}
```

## Conditional Validation with applyWhen

Three arguments: path, condition, schema function:

```ts
applyWhen(
  s.spouse,
  ({ valueOf }) => valueOf(s.maritalStatus) === 'married',
  (spousePath) => {
    required(spousePath.name);
    required(spousePath.email);
  },
);
```

## Reusable Schemas

```ts
import { schema } from '@angular/forms/signals';

const addressSchema = schema<Address>((s) => {
  required(s.street);
  required(s.city);
  required(s.zipCode);
  pattern(s.zipCode, /^\d{5}$/);
});

// Compose into larger form
orderForm = form(this.orderModel, (s) => {
  apply(s.billingAddress, addressSchema);
  apply(s.shippingAddress, addressSchema);
});
```

## Nested @for Loops

Angular does **NOT** have `$parent`. Store outer index with `let`:

```html
@for (item of myForm.items; track $index; let outerIdx = $index) {
  @for (option of item.options; track $index) {
    <button (click)="removeOption(outerIdx, $index)">Remove</button>
  }
}
```

## Updating Values

Signal Forms are model-driven. **NEVER** try to `.set()` on the form tree. Update the model signal:

```ts
// WRONG
this.myForm.name.set('John');

// CORRECT
this.model.update(m => ({ ...m, name: 'John' }));
```

## Standard Schema Integration (Zod, Valibot)

```ts
import { validateStandardSchema } from '@angular/forms/signals';
import * as z from 'zod';

const userSchema = z.object({
  email: z.email(),
  password: z.string().min(8),
});

userForm = form(this.model, (s) => {
  validateStandardSchema(s, userSchema);
});
```

## Error Structure

```ts
interface ValidationError {
  readonly kind: string;
  readonly message?: string;
}
```

- Return `undefined` (or `null`) from validators when there's no error.
- Prefer `undefined` over `null`.

## Server Errors on Submit

```ts
submit(this.myForm, async (field) => {
  const error = await this.api.save(field.$state.value());
  if (error) {
    return [{
      field: field.username,
      error: { kind: 'taken', message: 'Username already taken' },
    }];
  }
});
```

## Paths are NOT Signals

Inside the schema callback, paths (`s.field`) are **NOT** callable:

```ts
// WRONG
applyWhen(s.foo, () => s.foo() === 'x', ...);

// CORRECT
applyWhen(s.foo, ({ valueOf }) => valueOf(s.foo) === 'x', ...);
```

## Migration from Reactive Forms

For incremental migration, `@angular/forms/signals/compat` provides:
- `compatForm` — embed existing `FormGroup`/`FormControl` in a signal form
- `SignalFormControl` — drop-in for `FormControl`

Never reassign the model signal. Always use `.set()` or `.update()`.
